# **1\. Introduction** {#1.-introduction}

## **1.1. Purpose** {#1.1.-purpose}

- The main aim of the Online Course Management System (OCMS) to give an alternative to educators and students, mainly focus on university students to conduct and participate in lessons, intriguing functions with subject materials, and most importantly to have a “passive-active” way to track the course as a whole and progress specifically to you. The system aims to accomplish this by implementing a simple but modern, equipped with everything both sides of the classroom need to achieve the best results as possible.

## **1.2. Scope** {#1.2.-scope}

- The system includes account creation, user management, content management, assessments, announces and reporting, and other education tools

# **2\. User Requirements** {#2.-user-requirements}

## **2.1. Actors** {#2.1.-actors}

| \# | Actor | Description |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **1** | **Students** | A student uses the system to enroll in and manage courses, view their timetable, grades (including GPA and practice scores), access course materials, take tests, check attendance, and pay tuition |
| **2** | **Lecturers** | A lecturer uses the system to manage their assigned classes, upload course materials and tests, post announcements, enter and approve student grades, and monitor class attendance |
| **3** | **Admin**   | An administrator uses the system to create, edit, and delete user accounts; manage courses and class assignments (including assigning lecturers); approve grades; and oversee overall system operations |

## **3.2 Account Management**  {#3.2-account-management}

### **3.2.1 Login** {#3.2.1-login}

**Actors/Roles:** all roles with valid credentials

**Purpose:** Authenticate users so that only authorized actors can access their respective dashboards and functions

**Data Processing**

1. UI collects username and password and sends to back-end. Back-end looks up user record by username  
2. If found, compare the supplied password (after hashing) to stored password hash  
3. On match, issues session token/JWT and returns user profile & role  
4. On mismatch or any error, returns an error code/message

# **4\. Non-Functional Requirements** {#4.-non-functional-requirements}

## **4.1 External Interfaces** {#4.1-external-interfaces}

The OCMS shall expose the following external interfaces:

* **Web Browser Interface**: All user interactions (students, lecturers, administrators) shall occur through modern web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge). The UI layer shall consume RESTful JSON APIs served by the application back-end.

* **Authentication Service**: The system shall integrate with the institution’s Single Sign-On (SSO) provider via OAuth2/OpenID Connect for campus accounts.

* **Database Interface**: The application shall connect to a Microsoft SQL Server 2019 instance over a secure, encrypted channel (TLS 1.2). All SQL access shall be via stored procedures or parameterized queries.

* **Notification Service (Optional)**: When enabled, the system may call an external SMTP or messaging API (e.g. SendGrid) to deliver email or in-app notifications.

## **4.2 Quality Attributes** {#4.2-quality-attributes}

The following quality attributes specify the desired characteristics of the OCMS.

### **4.2.1 Usability** {#4.2.1-usability}

The OCMS shall provide an intuitive, web-based interface requiring no more than two hours of training for a new student or lecturer to perform core tasks (course registration, viewing grades, posting announcements). Standard UI elements (menus, forms, buttons) shall follow industry best-practices (e.g. Microsoft Fluent Design or Bootstrap conventions). All pages shall be navigable in no more than three clicks from the Dashboard. Error messages and confirmations shall be clear, concise, and displayed in context (in-line or toast notifications).

### **4.2.2 Reliability** {#4.2.2-reliability}

The system shall achieve 99.9 % uptime (no more than 8.8 hours of downtime per year), with planned maintenance windows scheduled outside business hours. It shall exhibit a Mean Time Between Failures (MTBF) of at least 1,000 hours and a Mean Time To Repair (MTTR) of no more than 2 hours. Grade calculations and data exports must be accurate to within 0.01 %. The system’s defect rate shall not exceed 0.5 bugs per KLOC, with critical defects (data loss, security breaches) fixed within 24 hours of detection.

### **4.2.3 Performance** {#4.2.3-performance}

Under typical load (up to 500 concurrent users), 90 % of page requests shall complete in under 2 seconds. End-to-end transactions—such as course enrollment or grade submission—shall complete in under 5 seconds. The system must support a peak throughput of 100 transactions per second and scale to 1,000 concurrent users with horizontal scaling. Server CPU utilization shall remain below 70 %, and memory usage below 8 GB on a standard 16 GB instance.

### **4.2.4 Security** {#4.2.4-security}

All data in transit shall use TLS 1.2 or higher. Sensitive data at rest (passwords, payment information) shall be encrypted with AES-256. Passwords must meet complexity rules (minimum eight characters, including uppercase, lowercase, digit, and symbol) and be hashed with a salt using bcrypt. Administrators shall authenticate via multi-factor authentication (MFA). Role-based access control shall prevent unauthorized access to any use case not permitted by the user’s role. Audit logs shall record every authentication event and CRUD operation with timestamp and user ID.

### **4.2.5 Maintainability** {#4.2.5-maintainability}

Source code shall follow the project’s style guide and include inline comments for all public methods. The codebase must achieve at least 80 % unit‐test coverage and 60 % integration‐test coverage. Build and deployment scripts (e.g. Azure DevOps pipelines or Docker Compose) shall be version-controlled. Any new feature shall include corresponding automated tests before merge.

### **4.2.6 Portability & Compatibility** {#4.2.6-portability-&-compatibility}

The OCMS shall be compatible with the two latest major versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari, and Edge on Windows, macOS, iOS, and Android. The UI shall be responsive, adapting to screen widths from 320 px (mobile) to 1920 px (desktop) without horizontal scrolling. Server‐side code shall be deployable on any Linux‐based container or Windows Server environment.

### **4.2.7 Backup & Recovery** {#4.2.7-backup-&-recovery}

Database backups shall occur daily at 02:00 AM, with a retention period of 30 days. Point-in-time restore must be possible up to 1 hour before failure. Application code and configuration shall be backed up on each successful production deployment.

# **5\. Requirement Appendix** {#5.-requirement-appendix}

## **5.1 Business Rules** {#5.1-business-rules}

| ID | Rule Definition |
| :---: | ----- |
| **BR \- 01** | Students may only enroll in courses during the official registration window for each semester |
| **BR \- 02** | A student’s total credit load per semester must not exceed 24 credits |
| **BR \- 03** | Tuition fees must be paid in full at least one week before the first day of classes each semester |
| **BR \- 04** | Students whose attendance in any course falls below 75% are not permitted to sit for that course’s final exam |
| **BR \- 05** | Lecturers must upload all core course materials (syllabus, lecture notes) at least three business days before the corresponding class session |
| **BR \- 06** | Lecturers must enter and finalize all student grades within seven calendar days after the end of the semester |
| **BR \- 07** | Administrators must approve or reject new course and class-section requests within five business days of submission |
| **BR \- 08** | User sessions expire after 30 minutes of inactivity; re-authentication is required to resume |
| **BR \- 09** | Users’ passwords must meet the institution’s complexity policy (minimum 8 characters, including uppercase, lowercase, digit and special character) |
| **BR \- 10** | The system must prevent students from enrolling in two courses whose scheduled meeting times overlap |

## **5.2 Common Requirements** {#5.2-common-requirements}

## 

| ID | Rule Definition |
| :---: | ----- |
| **CR \- 01** | Students may only enroll in courses during the official registration window for each semester |
| **CR \- 02** | The application shall maintain 99.9 % uptime (24 × 7 availability) |
| **CR \- 03** | All data in transit shall be encrypted using TLS 1.2 or higher |
| **CR \- 04** | All stored passwords must be hashed with a secure algorithm (e.g. bcrypt) and never stored in plaintext |
| **CR \- 05** | User sessions shall automatically expire after 30 minutes of inactivity, requiring re-authentication |
| **CR \- 06** | The UI shall be fully responsive and function correctly on desktop and mobile browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari) |
| **CR \- 07** | Daily backups of the database shall occur at 02:00 AM with a retention period of at least 30 days |
| **CR \- 08** | Audit logs shall record every create/update/delete action, including timestamp, user ID, and affected object |
| **CR \- 09** | The system shall enforce role-based access control so that users can only invoke use cases permitted by their role |
| **CR \- 10** | Error conditions shall be handled gracefully, presenting user-friendly messages and logging technical details |
